Only three per family and most DGE tools recommend at least 7 samples per group, so we will work on a species basis

Lets load the count data

# load gene count data, convert the column gene_id to row names, convert to a matrix
Pcal_counts <- read_tsv("Pcal_gene_counts.tsv", show_col_types = FALSE) %>% 
  column_to_rownames("gene_id") %>%
  as.matrix()

Are all the samples present in Pcal_counts?

# Call culumn names 
colnames(Pcal_counts) %in% Pcal_sampledata$sampleName
##  [1] TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE
## [16] TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE

We need to create a DESeq2 object to work with DESeq2. We combine the count and sample data using DESeqDataSetFromMatrix since we are working with a matrix. The design provides the groups over which we will do the DGE analysis. In this case it will be ~ condidtion with the species names. (There are other alternatives for HTSeq data etc.)

pre_Pcal_dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = Pcal_counts, 
                              colData = Pcal_sampledata, 
                              design = ~ condition)
## converting counts to integer mode

There could be systematic biases in the data. Meaning that for one sample all the genes have 2 times as many sequences than the average. We need to normalize this.

First we can filter out the genes that are not expressed in most of the samples. This is not explicitly necessary, but can save computational power. If the gene is expressed less than 5 times in more than 3 samples we dont keep that row. How does the 9 work?

# determine whether genes meet our threshold
keep <- rowSums(counts(pre_Pcal_dds) >= 5 ) >= 9

# filter the dds object to keep genes that meet the threshold
Pcal_dds <- pre_Pcal_dds[keep,]

# if you plan to use the filtered data set, make sure you use the filtered dds object in the following analysis

To normalize we first take the geometric mean per row Why geometric. We then see how different the value for the gene is proportionally per sample. Then we see what the of this is for all genes of per sample. We then normalize everything by this median which can be called the normalization factor. This is done using a function from DESeq2.

# Estimate the size factors
Pcal_dds <- estimateSizeFactors(Pcal_dds) 
sizeFactors(Pcal_dds) # Check the size factors

Logically the amount of samples with more or less reads should be approximately equal.

We then need to transform to improve estimated correlations or distances between genes? We use variance-stabilizing transformation because DESeq2 recommends it? We say blind=TRUE indicating we dont want to use the species grouping (the design in the dds object). This way it will transform everything at once. Only if conditions are very different use blind==FALSE

# Transform the data using the variance-stabilizing transformation
Pcal_vst <- vst(Pcal_dds, blind=TRUE)

The we use the PCA function from DESeq2. We take the top 1000 most variable genes ntop = 1000.

# PCA plot
plotPCA(Pcal_vst, intgroup=c("condition"), ntop = 1000)
## using ntop=1000 top features by variance

# plotPCA depends on ggplot2, so we can spice it up a bit:
plotPCA(Pcal_vst, intgroup=c("condition"), ntop = 1000) +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Dark2", name = "Host plant") +
  theme(legend.text = element_text(face = "italic"))
## using ntop=1000 top features by variance

# save your plot
ggsave("output/Pcal_vst_PC1_PC2.pdf", height = 6, width = 6)

If you want to use another PCA package for visualization you can get the transformed data assay(Pcal_vst)like so.

For the hierarchical clustering we need to calculate the distance between the samples. I imagine this works like calculating distance for phylogenies from sequences. Where you see the pairwise differences and then make a simple phylogeny based on that.

We first collect the data with assay(Pcal_vst) then we transpose using t() because the next function we use dist() works on rows.Then we need it as a matrix too.

Pcal_vst_dists <- dist(t(assay(Pcal_vst)))
Pcal_vst_mat <- as.matrix(Pcal_vst_dists)

Then simply run hclust()

Pcal_vst_hc <- hclust(Pcal_vst_dists)

Then we visualize using the pheatmap package (ComplexHeatmap, is also great). To personalize this will require reading into the heatmap manual.

# create a color palette
hmcol <- colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(9, "GnBu"))(100) 

# Plot the heatmap
Pcal_hm <- heatmap(Pcal_vst_mat, 
        Rowv=as.dendrogram(Pcal_vst_hc), 
        symm=TRUE,
        col = rev(hmcol),
        margin=c(13, 13), 
        cexRow = 0.75,
        cexCol = 0.75)

We can then simply save the results in a pdf file by first creating one and finishing it off with dev.off().

pdf(file = "output/Pcal_vst_sampleHeatmap.pdf", height = 6, width = 6)

Lets create a PCA biplot

First we set ntop=1000, so it is recognizable where we set our upper limit.We calculate the variance of the expression per gene and order the genes that are most different and put their names in a vector. After we only take the columns containing the names from the main dataset and transpose, because this package works on rows.

ntop = 1000

Pcal_vst_mat <- assay(Pcal_vst)
Pcal_vst_ntop_names <-names(sort(apply(Pcal_vst_mat, 1, var), decreasing = T))[1:ntop]
Pcal_vst_ntop <- t(Pcal_vst_mat[Pcal_vst_ntop_names,])

Then we simlpy calculate the PCs with prcomp() and we use the summary to see if it the same as our earlier PCA.

# calculate principal components
Pcal_vst_pca <- prcomp(Pcal_vst_ntop)

# make sure they match the PCA you made with plotPCA by looking at the summary of the PCA object. Does the proportion of the variance explained by PC1 match the % on the x axis from earlier?
summary(Pcal_vst_pca)

We take the variance explained in the first to PCs from the summary

pc1_prop <- summary(Pcal_vst_pca)$importance[2,1]
pc2_prop <- summary(Pcal_vst_pca)$importance[2,2]

We want to create a data frame of principal component values for each sample. They are in column x of Pcal_vst_pca. We need to change our rownames back to real columns for joining with dplyr. Then we join it to the sample data columns sampleName, condition and family using left_join. This will get the column on the left side of the data frame.

Pcal_vst_pca_df <- as.data.frame(Pcal_vst_pca$x) %>%
  rownames_to_column(var = "sampleName") %>% 
  left_join(dplyr::select(Pcal_sampledata, sampleName, condition, family)) 
## Joining with `by = join_by(sampleName)`

Now we want to create the loadings of the top 10 most variable genes

Pcal_vst_pca_loadings <- as.data.frame(Pcal_vst_pca$rotation[Pcal_vst_ntop_names,])%>%
  rownames_to_column(var = "geneID") %>% 
  head(10)

Now we can visualize with two ggplot geom thingies. Most importantly we scale the loadings by 200 to make them visible for the rest we also do a lot of other fancy ggplot stuff.

ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = Pcal_vst_pca_df,
             aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = condition, shape = family)) +
  geom_segment(data = Pcal_vst_pca_loadings,
               aes(x=0, y=0, xend=PC1*200, yend=PC2*200), 
               arrow = arrow(length=unit(0.5, 'cm')), color = "red") +
  annotate(geom = "text", 
           label = Pcal_vst_pca_loadings$geneID,
           x = Pcal_vst_pca_loadings$PC1*200, y = Pcal_vst_pca_loadings$PC2*200, 
           size = 3)+
  theme_bw() +
  labs( x = paste0("PC1 (", signif(pc1_prop*100,3), "%)"), 
        y = paste0("PC2 (", signif(pc2_prop*100,3), "%)")) +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Dark2", name = "Host plant") +
  theme(legend.text = element_text(face = "italic"))

Differential gene expression anaylis

The function DESeq2 performs the normalization of the counts using the size factors, estimates dispersion, and fits the linear model. By overwriting the old Pcal_dds variable we can add the new calculated values to out earlier created DESeqDataSet.

Pcal_dds <- DESeq(Pcal_dds)
## using pre-existing size factors
## estimating dispersions
## gene-wise dispersion estimates
## mean-dispersion relationship
## final dispersion estimates
## fitting model and testing
## -- replacing outliers and refitting for 46 genes
## -- DESeq argument 'minReplicatesForReplace' = 7 
## -- original counts are preserved in counts(dds)
## estimating dispersions
## fitting model and testing

The Wald test is often used for hypothesis testing with groups. In DESeq2 we provide groups with contrast. Lest see what contrast are possible in our design

resultsNames(Pcal_dds)
## [1] "Intercept"                 "condition_Salix_vs_Ribes"

Lets test Urtica vs Ribes. We can give the the contrast in a vector to the resultsfunction in DESeq2. Or name the contrast.

# specify the contrast by naming the factor you want to test 
# and the levels of the factor you want to compare.
contrast_U_R <- c("condition", "Urtica", "Ribes")

# extract the results for your specified contrast
Pcal_res_table_U_R <- results(Pcal_dds, contrast=contrast_U_R)

# this can alternatively be written using the names of the contrasts 
#Pcal_res_table_U_R <- results(Pcal_dds, name = "condition_Urtica_vs_Ribes") # do not run this code, the results are the same as the previous line

The Wald test calculates how likely it is that the difference in gene expression would occur randomly. The false discovery adjusted (Benjamini-Hochberg (BH)) p values for this test are stored in the padj column.

# sort results based on the padj
Pcal_res_table_U_R <- Pcal_res_table_U_R[order(Pcal_res_table_U_R$padj),]

# You will now have the smallest padj values at the top of your table
head(Pcal_res_table_U_R)

The column headers are:

  • baseMean: mean of normalized counts for all samples
  • log2FoldChange: log2 fold change or LFC
  • lfcSE: standard error of log2 fold change
  • stat: the Wald test statistic
  • pval: Wald test p-value
  • padj: Benjamini-Hochberg (BH) adjusted p-values

When specifying the contrast c("condition", "Urtica", "Ribes") you are really asking the question `How does Urtica (condition 1) differ relative to Ribes (condition 2), which should help when trying to specify your own contrasts.

Normally, we expect to see significant fold changes across the range of expression levels.

Then they likely have low counts and are not significant because of it. Using DESeq2, there is a way to shrink the log2 fold change for genes with low counts so that you can have more confidence in the fold change estimates. Fuzzy works best when the data is not transformed and the mean is scaled to 0.

dat.s <- standardise(dat)

# you can remove the unscaled expressionSet
rm(dat)

Fuzzy c-means is better suited for us as it does not assign genes to cluster if they are in between cluster and thus they want skew the cluster because they look slightly more than the others.

m1 <- mestimate(dat.s)
m1
## [1] 1.109573

We want the lowest distance to the centroid, for up to 22 clusters with steps of 1 starting at 2. Then we store this number of clusters in a vector. 3?

Dmin(dat.s, m=m1, crange=seq(2,22,1), repeats=3, visu=TRUE)

Pcal_DE_U_R_fcm_results <- mfuzz(dat.s,centers=c_estimate,m=m1)

geneUniverse <- names(geneID2GO)

There will be two analyses. One for up- and one for down-regulated genes. We filter both based on whether they have a significance lower than 0.001 and an LFC greater than +/- 1. We should save the list as these will be the genes of our interest.

up_U_R <- rownames(Pcal_res_table_U_R %>% 
                           data.frame() %>%
                           filter(padj < 0.01 & log2FoldChange > 1))

write.csv(up_U_R, "up_U_R.csv", row.names = FALSE)

down_U_R <- rownames(Pcal_res_table_U_R %>%
                             data.frame() %>% 
                             filter(padj < 0.01 & log2FoldChange < -1))

write.csv(down_U_R, "down_U_R.csv", row.names = FALSE)

Generally, GSEA is best applied to an intermediately-sized gene set. Too small, it is unlikely that any GO term will occur often enough to be enriched. Instead, you can easily look at the genes themselves and make conclusions about their functions. Too large relative to the annotated gene universe and terms will occur in the list just as often as expected because youve sampled all the genes! Rachel

Mesmerize at the power of a for-loop. Here instead of doing it for biological processes we do it for molecular processes.

# Starting with BP
GO_category="MF"

DEgenes_list <- list(down_U_R, up_U_R)
names(DEgenes_list) <- c("down_U_R", "up_U_R")

for (i in 1:2){
  # define candidate list
  genesOfInterest.bv <- DEgenes_list[[i]]
  
  # placing this within brackets causes all the lines to run in a single block
  # it can help you keep track of code that you usually run together
  
  geneList.bv <- factor(as.integer(geneUniverse %in% genesOfInterest.bv))
  names(geneList.bv) <- geneUniverse
  
  # Create a new topGO GSEA objected
  myGOdata.bv <- new("topGOdata",
                     description="Candidate genes", 
                     ontology=GO_category, 
                     allGenes=geneList.bv, 
                     annot = annFUN.gene2GO, 
                     gene2GO = geneID2GO, 
                     nodeSize = node_size)                                       
  
  # classic Fisher
  resultClassic <- runTest(myGOdata.bv, algorithm="classic", statistic="fisher")
  
  # Fisher with parent-child algorithm
  resultParentchild <- runTest(myGOdata.bv, algorithm="parentchild", statistic="fisher")
 top_nodes <-  sum(resultParentchild@score < 0.05)
  # Create a GSEA results table
  temp <- GenTable(myGOdata.bv,
                   classicFisher = resultClassic,
                   parentchildFisher = resultParentchild,
                   orderBy = "parentchildFisher",
                   topNodes = top_nodes)
  assign(paste0("allRes_MF_", names(DEgenes_list)[[i]]), temp)
}

# Starting with BP
GO_category="MF"

DEgenes_list <- list(down_U_S, up_U_S)
names(DEgenes_list) <- c("down_U_S", "up_U_S")

for (i in 1:2){
  # define candidate list
  genesOfInterest.bv <- DEgenes_list[[i]]
  
  # placing this within brackets causes all the lines to run in a single block
  # it can help you keep track of code that you usually run together
  
  geneList.bv <- factor(as.integer(geneUniverse %in% genesOfInterest.bv))
  names(geneList.bv) <- geneUniverse
  
  # Create a new topGO GSEA objected
  myGOdata.bv <- new("topGOdata",
                     description="Candidate genes", 
                     ontology=GO_category, 
                     allGenes=geneList.bv, 
                     annot = annFUN.gene2GO, 
                     gene2GO = geneID2GO, 
                     nodeSize = node_size)                                       
  
  # classic Fisher
  resultClassic <- runTest(myGOdata.bv, algorithm="classic", statistic="fisher")
  
  # Fisher with parent-child algorithm
  resultParentchild <- runTest(myGOdata.bv, algorithm="parentchild", statistic="fisher")
  top_nodes <-  sum(resultParentchild@score < 0.05)
  # Create a GSEA results table
  temp <- GenTable(myGOdata.bv,
                   classicFisher = resultClassic,
                   parentchildFisher = resultParentchild,
                   orderBy = "parentchildFisher",
                   topNodes = top_nodes)
  assign(paste0("allRes_MF_", names(DEgenes_list)[[i]]), temp)
}
